    "summary": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Basing a broad conclusion on a small sample or the making of a determination without all of the information required to do so.",
        "spans": []
      }
    ],
    "description": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "In logic, \"generalization\" refers to the reasoning process by which a general conclusion is inferred from a particular premise or premises. There is more than one kind of generalization, but the one relevant to this fallacy is statistical generalization. In a statistical generalization, one infers something about a whole group based on a part of that group. In statistics, the group that we're interested in is called \"the population\" and the part that we examine is called \"the sample\". In order for such an inference to be cogent, the sample must be representative of the whole population. However, one way in which a sample can fail to be representative is for it to be too small. A \"hasty\" generalization is too quick, that is, it jumps to a conclusion before acquiring sufficient evidence to justify it.",
